sition them in wider debates on aesthetics and society. The book also considers the well-established topics of realism and arthouse auteurism, and re-thinks film history by investigating the presence of melodrama in neorealism and post-war modernism. It places film within its broader cultural context to trace the connections of canonical melodramatists like Visconti and Matarazzo to traditions of opera, the musical theatre of the sceneggiata, visual arts, and magazines. In so doing it seeks to capture the artistry and emotional experiences found within a truly popular form.Key Features Connects less established areas of research such as popular neorealism to more well-known subjects such as domestic melodramaProvides an analysis of cineopera or opera filmHelps to pioneer the area of popular Italian cinemaContributes to both Italian Studies and Film Studies"  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aMelodrama in motion pictures. 0aMelodrama, Italian. 0aMotion pictureszItalyxHistoryy20th century. 0aMotion pictureszItalyxHistory. 0aMotion pictureszItaly. 4aFilm, Media & Cultural Studies. 7aART / Popular Culture.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311078045140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780748656431423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780748656431/original  a978-3-11-078045-1  Edinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_AD  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_AD  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK